From d0cfd7b6605dac15471240724dec03bb9b91231e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Sat, 4 Jul 2026 15:39:40 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] dar-pot: bind guest-ns launchd lifetime to darlingserver
 (PR_SET_PDEATHSIG)

Root fix for dar-pot: orphaned mldr guest processes leak across sessions and
destabilize fresh boots ("semaphore_timedwait -111", half-set-up root-owned
workdir).

ROOT CAUSE (darlingserver.cpp): darlingserver runs in the host PID ns and
creates the guest PID namespace ONCE via clone(CLONE_NEWPID) -- that clone child
is launchd, PID 1 of the new ns; every mldr guest is a descendant of launchd
inside that ns. The kernel cascade-kills a PID ns when its PID-1 dies, so killing
launchd kills all guests. But darlingserver is launchd's PARENT, OUTSIDE the ns.
If darlingserver dies (crash / SIGKILL / launcher exit) while launchd lives, the
ns persists and every guest keeps running, orphaned and reparented -- they
accumulate until the next fresh boot wedges. That is dar-pot.

FIX: the launchd clone child sets prctl(PR_SET_PDEATHSIG, SIGKILL) so that when
darlingserver dies for ANY reason, ns-PID-1 receives SIGKILL; the kernel then
cascade-kills the whole guest namespace. No guest can outlive its server, so
none can accumulate. This also hardens `darling shutdown`: even if its
launchd_pid read races, SIGKILLing darlingserver now cascade-kills launchd (and
thus guests) via the pdeathsig.

Placement is load-bearing: AFTER perma_drop_privileges (a credential change
clears pdeathsig) and BEFORE spawnLaunchd (no guest may exist before the binding
is armed). The pdeathsig survives the exec into mldr/launchd (mldr is not
set-uid). The clone->prctl parent-death race is covered by the existing
childWaitFDs handshake, which we now reach only after arming the signal. The
fix is at manifest-rev (the clone region is byte-identical across the homebrew /
perf / A0 stacks), so it is profile-independent.

RED-TDD gate (tests/pot_lifetime_binding_test.c + run-pot-lifetime-binding.sh):
a hermetic host-model that reproduces the exact server->launchd(CLONE_NEWPID)
->guest topology and asserts a guest must NOT survive its server.
  RED  (nobind): no pdeathsig -> killing the server leaves the guest alive
                 (GUEST-SURVIVED) -- the shipped bug reproduces.
  GREEN (bind):  pdeathsig(SIGKILL) -> killing the server cascade-kills the
                 guest (GUEST-REAPED).
Both arms pass; the gate cleans up its own model processes (no orphan leak).
Empirically verified: ns-PID-1 getppid()==0 across the ns boundary (so a
getppid race guard is inapplicable), and pdeathsig fires on parent death.

bead: dar-pot

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 src/darlingserver.cpp             |  18 ++
 tests/pot_lifetime_binding_test.c | 357 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 tests/run-pot-lifetime-binding.sh |  78 +++++++
 3 files changed, 453 insertions(+)
